And Jesus left that place and went to the region of Syro-Phoenicia and to the area of Padra.
A Canaanite woman came to him, living in that area, and began to cry out: "Have mercy on me, Lord, Son of David. My daughter is possessed by a demon and is suffering greatly."
Jesus said nothing to her. Then his disciples came to him and asked him, "Drive her away, for she is following us and is making a noise."
He said: "I have not sent except to the wild cattle of the lost tribe of Israel."
But the woman approached him and prostrated herself before him, saying: "O Lord, help me."
Then Jesus answered her: "It is not proper to take the children's food and throw it to the dogs."
She said: "That's true, sir, but even dogs eat from what falls from their owners' table."
At that time Jesus replied to her, "Woman, your faith is great; let it be done for you." And at that moment her daughter was healed. Jesus healed many.
And Jesus left that place and went to a region near the Sea of Galilee. He climbed a hill and sat there.
A large crowd came to him, and with them were a man with a withered hand, a blind man, a lame man, and many others who were suffering from various illnesses. They placed them at Jesus' feet, and he healed them.
The crowd was amazed when they saw the mute speak, the lame walk, the disabled move, and the blind see. They glorified God of Israel. Jesus fed more than four thousand.
Jesus then said to his disciples, "I have compassion on these people; they have been with me for three days and have nothing to eat. I do not want to send them away hungry, lest they faint along the way."
His disciples said to him: "Where will we get enough bread to feed this crowd in such a remote place?"
Then Jesus said to them, "How many loaves do you have?" They replied, "Seven loaves and a few small fish."
Then Jesus commanded the people to sit down on the ground.
And he took the seven loaves and the fish, gave thanks, broke the loaves, and gave them to the disciples to distribute to all.
So everyone ate and was filled. Then they gathered the excess barley, and there were seven full baskets.
The number of the eaters was four thousand men, excluding women and children.
And when Jesus had sent the multitudes away, He got into a boat and went to the region of Gadara.
Jewish leaders are testing Jesus
The Friscians and the Sadoonites came to Jesus to test him, and asked him to give them a sign of God's support for him.
Then Jesus replied: "When evening comes, people say, 'The weather will be fine, for the sky is red.'"
In the early morning, you say: "Today will be stormy, because the sky is reddish and overcast." You improve your interpretation of weather signs, but you do not improve your understanding of the times in which you live!
This wicked, corrupt generation seeks a sign to believe. And a sign will only be given them—Jonah's. Then Jesus left them and withdrew from them. Lack of understanding
And as the disciples crossed to the other side of the lake, they forgot to bring bread.
Jesus said to them: "Be on your guard and beware of the leaven of the Pharisees and the Sadducees."
Then the students began to speak and say to each other: "But we didn't bring any bread!"
Jesus knew what they were saying, and He said to them: "You of little faith, why are you arguing among yourselves about the lack of bread?"
Did you not realize afterwards? Don't you remember the five loaves for five thousand, and how many baskets of broken bread did you gather?
Do you not remember the seven loaves for four thousand, and how much flour did you gather?
Why do you not understand that I was not speaking to you about ordinary bread, but warning you to protect yourselves from the leaven of the Pharisaeans and the Sadducees?"
